did.unittitle: Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority metrorail specifications
did.abstract: The WMATA Metrorail Specifications collection is comprised primarly of technical specifications and contracts related to the construction of Metrorail. The collection consists of unbound letter-size documents, bound letter-size reports and specifications, oversize reports and specifications, and blueprints.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority, WMATA, with central offices in Washington, DC, is the private agency charged with the coordination and operation of mass transit in the National Capital Region. This area includes Montgomery and Prince George's Counties in Maryland, Arlington, the District of Columbia, and Fairfax County in Virginia.

The Interim Board of Directors of WMATA first met in mid-October, 1966, chaired by Brig. Gen. Jackson Graham, formerly Engineering Commissioner for the District. WMATA was formally established on February 20, 1967. WMATA formally received its charter in September 1967.

WMATA superseded the National Capital Transportation Agency (NCTA); a federal agency established by President Eisenhower in 1960 and inherited the bus and rail plans of the NCTA. For bus operations, WMATA bought out the routes from the private bus companies operating within its purview (with the exception of Montgomery County's "Ride-On" system) and established a single operation, Metrobus, to serve in their place.

For the creation of Metrorail, popularly known as "the Metro," routes, designs, and plans were finalized by the late 1960s. Work on the subway component began immediately upon the creation of WMATA. DeLeuw, Cather were retained as chief engineering consultants. The firm of Harry Weese and Associates were named chief architectural consultants. Weese was sent on a worldwide tour of subway systems, in order to draw inspiration and ideas for possible station architecture. The final design, agreed upon by a special committee that included the District of Columbia Board of Fine Arts and several artists and architects, was proposed in 1968.

First ground was broken for the subway above the future Judiciary Square station on December 9, 1969. The Metro ran its first day of revenue service, on the abbreviated Red Line beginning at Dupont Circle, in June 1976. Public response was enthusiastic. The system was a highlight of the Bicentennial celebrations one month later, during which it transported thousands of visitors.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The WMATA Metrorail Specifications collection is so named because the bulk of the collection is technical specifications and contracts related to the construction of Metrorail. The collection consists of unbound letter-size documents, bound letter-size reports and specifications, oversize reports and specifications, and blueprints.

The collection is an artificial one, consisting of several distinct and unrelated types of documents. The earliest documents date from 1962, and were generated by the WMATA's predecessor agency, the NCTA. Most of these deal with highway development. The bulk of the material dates from 1972-78 and contains of a distinct series of oversize and letter-size bound volumes. These volumes are contract specifications for different sections of Metrorail tunnels, and each bears the name of the contractor that won the bid, as well as the contract number. The collection's third district group of documents consists of minutes of meetings, and related documents, generated by meetings of the Board of Directors and with individual contractors.

The collection's Reports and, especially, Specifications series are highly technical engineering documents. They are valuable for their comprehensive engineering detail and descriptions, through which the evolution, design and construction of the Metro system can be studied in detail. Not all routes, nor all sections along one route, are covered in the available contract specifications. The meeting minutes are valuable for their insight into administrative planning. However, the Board of Directors minutes are present (and presumed complete) only for 1971 and 1974, and the contractor meeting minutes are incomplete for the years covered, namely 1972 through 1978, with several months missing altogether.

Researchers are also advised that six titles, removed from the Metrorail Specifications Collection, have been processed elsewhere as shelved items. Consult library indexes for these titles. The are: "New York City Transit Authority Invitation to Contractors" for Contracts C-213-1 through C-213-3; Contract R-30-A; Contract R-33; and Contract R-40; "District of Columbia Department of Highways and Traffic, Standard Specifications for Highways and Structures", 1974; and "State of Maryland, State Roads Commission, Specifications for Materials, Highways, Bridges, and Incidental Structures", March 1968.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into four series: Meeting minutes, Reports, Specifications, and Oversize documents.

did.unittitle: Meeting minutes

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains meeting minutes for the Board of Directors and meeting minutes for the contractors. The materials cover the dates 1971-78. In addition to the minutes the Board of Directors section has additional documents used by the WMATA Board at meetings. The contractors minutes are for meetings with various contractors working for WMATA. All these minutes provide a valuable reference for senior Authority decision making.

Reports

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains bound volumes that fall within four main sections including budget and finances, handbooks and manuals, miscellaneous, and transit system development. These volumes are less technical than the specifications series. The documents are primarily text with supporting illustrations. The material covers the dates 1962-81.

The budget and finances section contains reports from various WMATA sources that detail projected or actual departmental or overall expenses. Handbooks and manuals consists of a construction safety manual. The miscellaneous section includes environmental impact studies and proposed routes. The transit system development section consists of reports detailing development of the Metro system.

Specifications

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series is comprised of documents that contain diagrammatic explanations of Metrorail route contracts and other technical matters. The dates covered are 1956-71.

The section for bridges, highways, and roads contains volumes that detail the construction and layout of non-rail routes. The miscellaneous section includes a route feasibility study and construction designs. Rail rapid transit specifications are those that deal exclusively with Metrorail routes and contracts. The route designs cover the routes themselves. The support equipment documents contain contracts issued for equipment such as fire extinguishers and kiosks.

These reports and specifications provide a useful technical adjunct to the more administrative documents found in other Metro-related collections. They pinpoint projected starting and completion dates, names of subcontractors, and the amount of work actually undertaken on each section of tunnel.

Oversize documents

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains bound reports and specifications that needed oversize boxes for archival storage and covers the dates 1959-80. The material is arranged with groupings for series one through three with an additional section in the series Specifications to accommodate documents generated by agencies other than NCTA or WMATA. All reports and specification documents are arranged alphabetically. The blueprints including map-size folders related to track switching procedures are arranged in numerical order by drawing number and then by further identifying number.

The reports section includes documents for the budget and finances and other miscellaneous topics that outline fiscal plans, feasibility studies, and environmental impact studies. The Specifications section of oversize documents is divided into the following subjects; bridges, highways, and roads, miscellaneous, and rail rapid transit. The rail rapid transit section is further divided into route designs and support equipment as well as specification documents produced by other transit agencies including Metropolitan Atlanta Region Transit Authority and Southeast Michigan Transit Authority.
